UilaAdapN, &c. 
for wilaAdapN, &c.: 
see art. wld

† Evil in disposition, applied to a man; 
and so with p {UiloqapN} applied to a woman: 
and the latter, a [demon of the kind called] siEolaAp; because of its evil, or malignant, nature: (TA:) and a bold woman; (Lth, Ḳ;) for the same reason. (TA.)

It also denotes the end of a space of time; 
[signifying To, till, or until;] as in the saying [in the Ḳur ii. 183], vum-a Oatim-uwA AlS-iyaAma UilaI All-ayoli [Then complets ye the fasting to, or till, or until, the night]. (Mughnee, Ḳ.) 
[Hence, UilaI Oano (followed by a mansoob aor.) Till, or until: and UilaI mataI Till, or until, what time, or when? i. e. how long? and also to, till, or until, the time when. See also the last sentence in this paragraph.]

It is also used to show the grammatical agency of the noun governed by it, after a verb of wonder; or after a noun of excess importing love or hatred; 
[as in maA OaHab-ahu UilaI-a How lovely, or pleasing, is he to me! (TA in art. Hb,) and maA OabogaDahu UilaI-a How hateful, or odious, is he to me! (Ṣ in art. bgD;) and] as in the saying [in the Ḳur xii. 33], rab-i Als-ijonu OaHab-u UilaI-a [O my Lord, the prison is more pleasing to me]. (Mughnee, Ḳ.) 
[This usage is similar to that explained in the next sentence.]

hom.sense:
Oaliy-apN [A falling short; or a falling short of what is requisite, or what one ought to do; or a flagging, or remissness; and slowness, or tardiness:] a subst. from OalaA as signifying qaS-ara and Oaliy-apF. (M.) 
Hence the prov., (M,) Uil-aA HaDiy-apF falaA Oaliy-apF, i. e. If I be not in favour, and high estimation, I will not cease seeking, and labouring, and wearying myself, to become so: (M, Ḳ:*) or if thou fail of good fortune in that which thou seekest, fall not short, or flag not, or be not remiss, in showing love, or affection, to men; may-be thou wilt attain somewhat of that which thou wishest: originally relating to a woman who becomes displeasing to her husband: (Ṣ in art. HZw:) it is one of the proverbs of women: one says, if I be not in favour, and high estimation, with my husband, I will not fall short, or flag, or be remiss, in that which may render me so, by betaking myself to that which he loveth: (T and TA in art. HZw:) Meyd says that the two nouns are in the accus. case because the implied meaning is Uil-aA Oakuno HaZiy-apF falaA Oakuno Oaliy-apF; the latter noun being [accord. to him] 
for MliyapN↓, for which it may be put for the sake of conformity [with the former]; and the former having the signification of the pass. part. n. of OaHoZaI, or that of the part. n. of HaZiIa [or HaZiyato]. (Ḥar p. 78.)

entry.sense:
Oum-N also relates to inanimate things that have growth; as in Oum-u AlX-ajarapi [The mother of the tree]; and Oum-u Aln-axolapi [the mother of the palm-tree]; and Oum-u Almawozipa [the mother of the banana-tree; 
of which see an ex. 
in art. mwz]; and the like. (M, TA.)

It is also an inceptive word, used in the manner of OalaA: (M:) followed by OalaA, it is syn. with OalaA: (Ṣ:) 
[meaning Now: or now surely: or] both of these meaning verily, or truly; i. c. Haq-FA: and for this reason Sb allows one's saying, OamaA Un-ah munoTalqN and OamaA Oan-ahu munoTalqN [Verily, or truly, he is going away]; with kesr after the manner of OalaA Uin-ahu, and with fet-ḥ after the manner of Haq-FA Oan-ahu: and hamaA waQll-ehi laqado kaAna kacaA is mentioned as meaning OamaA waQll-ehi 
[&c., i. e. Verily, or truly, by God, such a thing did indeed happen]; the h being a substitute for the hemzeh: (M:) so too HamaI wQll-eh [or HamaA wQll-eh]: (Ṣgh and Ḳ in art. HmI:) it denotes the truth of the words which follow it; as when you say, OamaA Uin-a zayodFA EaAqilN, meaning Truly, or properly speaking, not tropically, Zeyd is intelligent; and Oam-aA w Qll-eh qad Daraba zayodN EamorFA [Truly,, &c., by God, Zeyd beat, or struck, Amr]: (Ṣ in art. Amw:) 
[in other words,] it corroborates an oath and a sentence; 


as in OamaA waQll-eh laYino soharotu laka layolapF laOa daEan-aka naAdimFA [Verily, or now surely, by God, if I remain awake for thee a night, then will I indeed leave thee repenting]; and OamaA law Ealimotu makaAnaka laOazoEajotuka minohu [Verily, or now surely, if I had known thy place of being, then had I unsettled thee, or removed thee, from it]; and OamaA Uin-ahu larajulN kariymN [Verily, or now surely, he is (emphatically) a generous man]: (T:) or it is an inceptive particle, used in the manner of OalaA; 
[meaning now: or now surely:] (Mughnee:) or a particle used to give notice of what is about to be said: only put before a proposition 
[as in exs. mentioned above]: (TA:) and often occurring before an oath 
[as in exs. mentioned above]: and sometimes its hemzeh is changed into h or E, before the oath; each with the A remaining; 
[written hamaA or EamaA;] and with the A elided; 
[written hama or Eama;] or with the A elided, but without the substitution; 
[written Oama;] and when An-a occurs after OamaA, it is with kesr, as it is after OalaA: and it also means Haq-FA [verily, or truly]: 
or OaHq-FA [verily? or truly?]: 
accord. to different opinions: and in this case, An-a after it is with fet-ḥ, as it is after Haq-aA: accord. to Ibn-Kharoof, this is a particle: but some say that it is a noun in the sense of Haq-FA: and others, that it consists of two words, namely, the interrogative hemzeh and maA as a noun in the sense of XaIoCN; i. e. OacAlika AlX-aIoCu Haq-N [is that thing ture?]; so that the meaning is OaHaq-FA: 
[if so, OamaA Oan-ah munoTalqN means Verily, or truly, is he going away?] and this, which is what Sb says, is the correct opinion: maA is virtually in the accus. case, as an adverbial noun, like as Haq-FA is literally: and Oan-a with its complement is an inchoative, of which the adverbial noun is the enunciative: 
but Mbr says that Haq-FA is the inf. n. of yaHiq-u, which is suppressed, and that On-a with its complement is an agent. (Mughnee.)

OunuwHN: 
[see 1:] it is also explained as signifying A sound like that which is termed zafiyrN, arising from grief, or anger, or repletion of the belly, or jealousy: (L:) a sound accompanied by a reiterated hemming in the throat (SawotN maEa tanaHonuHK): (Aṣ:) and a sound that is heard from a man's inside, with breathing, and a shortness of breath, or panting for breath, which affects fat men; 
as also OaniyHN↓. (L.)

